               <p>A contemporary of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2189.xml"/>Samuel Wesley
                     Jr</persName>. at Westminster School and Christ Church, Leybourne became fellow
                  of Brasenose College, <placeName>Oxford</placeName>, in <date when="1717"
                     >1717</date>, <seg ana="degree">BD</seg> and <seg ana="degre">DD</seg> in <date
                     when="1731">1731</date>. He was rector of St. Dunstan&apos;s,
                     <placeName>Stepney</placeName>, <date when="1729">1729</date>, and of St.
                  Anne&apos;s, <placeName>Limehouse</placeName>, from <date when="1730">1730</date>
                  until his death. He was buried in <placeName>Bath Abbey</placeName> in the grave
                  of his second wife, <persName>Rebeccah Towne</persName> of
                     <placeName>Stratford-at-Bow, Essex</placeName>, whom he was licensed to marry
                     <date when="1733-01-20">Jan. 20, 1733</date>. For some time it had seemed
                  likely that Leybourne would marry <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2179.xml"
                     />Emily Wesley</persName>, but &apos;a near relation&apos; (apparently her
                  brother <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2189.xml"/>Samuel</persName>) and her
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2193.xml"/>mother</persName> intervened.
                  See <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2179.xml"/>Emily</persName>&apos;s letter
                  to <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>, <date
                     when="1725-04-07">Apr. 7, 1725</date>; and <hi rend="italic">Alumni
                     Oxonienses</hi>.</p>
            </person>
